In software design, some objects are meant to be shared across the entire application. Think of a configuration manager, a database connection, or a logger. You donâ€™t want to create multiple instances of these â€” just one that is reused everywhere. Thatâ€™s exactly where the Singleton Pattern comes in.
The Singleton Pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it.
Itâ€™s part of the Creational Design Patterns â€” patterns focused on object creation.
Think of a government. Thereâ€™s only one Prime Minister (ideally ðŸ˜„). If you try to create a new one, it should refer to the existing one.
